{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":32613,"record_hash":"sha256:00ab2c3372415b224cf05c48f50fec75c1a3e28b46a73085d10180c5b2833ca7","timestamp":"2026-05-11T18:08:26.573Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n1. **Fix now: retry classification is too broad**  \\n   [sync.rs:40](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/sync.rs:40) retries push failures when `is_non_fast_forward()` says retryable, but [sync.rs:168](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/sync.rs:168) treats any error containing `\\\"rejected\\\"` as non-fast-forward. Remote hook/policy failures often say “remote rejected” or “pre-receive hook declined”, so sync can repeat side-effecting pushes up to 5 times and then obscure the real error behind retry behavior. Narrow this to actual non-ff signals like `non-fast-forward`, `fetch first`, maybe `stale info`, or return a structured push error from `push_scope_ref`.\\n\\n2. **Fix now, small: `sync --remote \\\"\\\"` validation is in the wrong layer/order**  \\n   `Command::Sync` accepts a raw `String` at [cli.rs:31](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:31), then [cli.rs:143](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:143) resolves the workdir before [sync.rs:50](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/sync.rs:50) rejects an empty remote. That means cheap CLI input validation happens after Git discovery, and error order depends on repo presence. Mirror `non_empty_path` with a `non_empty_remote` parser so CLI owns argument validation before repo/business logic.\\n\\n**Leave Alone**\\n\\n- The repo/worktree normalization looks clean after the split: `cli.rs` resolves the workdir once via [cli.rs:122](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:122), capture canonicalizes only the transcript source at [capture.rs:13](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/capture.rs:13), and `gitmeta.rs` just writes to the supplied repo path. I don’t see duplicated repo discovery inside business/storage logic.\\n- `agentlog_scope()` in [gitmeta.rs:132](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:132) is borderline because only sync calls it, but it describes the storage key scope, not fetch/push behavior. I’d leave it unless more scoped GitMeta operations appear.\\n- Capture and association ordering is sane: parse/read happens before writes, and association only runs after `record_transcript` returns a session key at [cli.rs:128](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/cli.rs:128).\\n\\nValidation: `cargo test -p but-agentlog` passes, 26 tests.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T18:08:26.573Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}